 Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Barclay","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name of English origin, from any of several places so called, such as Berkley in Somerset or Berkeley in Gloucestershire, both named in Old English with <i>be(o)rc</i> ‘birch’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","History: The surname was brought to Scotland from southwestern England in the 12th century; Walter de Berchelai or Berkelai was Chamberlain of Scotland in 1165. It was long assumed that they were from the family that held Berkeley Castle in Gloucestershire, but the historian G. W. S. Barrow (1973, <i>The Kingdom of the Scots</i>) adduced evidence that they are more probably from Berkley in Somerset."],"variants":[{"name":"Barkley","meanings":["English and northern Irish (Antrim): variant of   Barclay  .","Americanized form of German   Berkel   or of some other similar (like-sounding) German surname."]},{"name":"Barclift","meanings":["Perhaps an altered form of Scottish   Barclay  ."]},{"name":"Berkeley","meanings":["English: habitational name from one or more of the numerous places so named, such as Berkeley in Gloucestershire, named in Old English with <i>be(o)rc</i> ‘birch’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. Compare Scottish   Barclay  .","Jewish (American): adoption of the English surname (see 1 above) in place of   Berkowitz  ."]},{"name":"Brickley","meanings":["English and Irish: metathesized form of   Barclay  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret de Barclay had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with Hugh Ross of Rarichies, 1st of Balnagown."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","1329–1374":"1329–1374","1344–Female":"1344–Surnud","1365–1401":"1365–1401","–Female":"Surnud","1401":"1401","AFT. 1344":"pärast 1344","1344":"1344","1365":"1365","1374":"1374","1329":"1329","Ross, Scotland":"Ross, Lanarkshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","1329–1374":"1329–1374","1344–Female":"1344–Kuollut","1365–1401":"1365–1401","–Female":"Kuollut","1401":"1401","AFT. 1344":"1344 jälkeen","1344":"1344","1365":"1365","1374":"1374","1329":"1329","Ross, Scotland":"Ross, Lanarkshire, Scotland"},"fr":{"–":"Décédée","1329–1374":"1329–1374","1344–Female":"1344–Décédée","1365–1401":"1365–1401","–Female":"Décédée","1401":"1401","AFT. 1344":"après 1344","1344":"1344","1365":"1365","1374":"1374","1329":"1329","Ross, Scotland":"Ross, Lanarkshire, Écosse","lifeSummary":